                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d116">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">808.24/899</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Adviser on Political Relations</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-29">August 29,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Chinese Ambassador read to me this morning from a letter which he had just
                    received by air mail from the Secretary-General of the People’s Political
                    Council, at Chungking, who is an Adviser to Chiang Kai-shek on Foreign Affairs.
                    In the course of this letter the writer said, in substance: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Our source of military supplies is now confined to the transcontinental
                            route of the northwest. But the Soviet Union does not seem to have much
                            enthusiasm for increasing supplies to us or for permitting us to import
                            arms and munitions through Vladivostok. Negotiations on those two
                            matters have had so far no results. For this reason, we must concentrate
                            our effort on the reopening of the Burma Road.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">tanley</hi>] K. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >ornbeck</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
